{"cursor":"1584","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'[[Aramaean kings|King]] Rezin of [[Aram Damascus|Aram]]'\n( [http://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation?lang=eng LDS.org: \"Book\nof Mormon Pronunciation Guide\"] (retrieved 2012-02-25), -ified from\nÂ«rÄÂ´zÄ­nÂ» ) or 'Rasin of Syria' in DRB (; ) ruled from Damascus during the\n8th century BC. During his reign he was a tributary of King Tiglath-pileser III\nof Assyria. Lester L. Grabbe, Ancient Israel: What Do We Know and How Do We\nKnow It? (New York: T&T Clark, 2007): 134\n\nRezin's reign ended around 732 BC when Tiglath-pileser sacked Damascus and\nannexed Aram. ibid. According to the Bible, the sack of Damascus was\ninstigated by King Ahaz of Judah and ended in Rezin's execution (). The\nexecution of Rezin is neither confirmed nor disconfirmed by independent\nevidence. Grabbe, Ancient Israel, 149\n\nAccording to 2 Kings Rezin allied with Pekah, son of Remaliah, against Ahaz. The\ndefeat of both kings is promised to Ahaz in the Immanuel prophecy , linked to\nthe birth of a child who will be an infant, possibly Ahaz' royal heir Hezekiah,\nwhen this takes place. Whittaker, H. A. Isaiah Biblia, Cannock\n","linknr":121,"url":"Rezin","recorded":1364048051,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Rezin&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Rezin&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/lo